13:45.925 --> 13:50.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He is president of the Brennan
Center for
Justice at the NYU School of
Law.

13:50.196 --> 13:52.565 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He also worked for President
Bill Clinton.

13:52.598 --> 13:56.802 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And William Jeffress, he is a
trial lawyer
who has worked on criminal and
civil cases

13:56.836 --> 13:58.571 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
at Baker Botts.

13:58.604 --> 14:02.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of his best known cases was
defending
Scooter Libby, the chief of
staff to former

14:02.775 --> 14:04.376 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Vice President Dick Cheney.

14:04.410 --> 14:06.579 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mr. Jeffress, let me begin with
you.

14:06.612 --> 14:10.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm sure you have heard the news
that Bob
Mueller, the former FBI
director, has now

14:10.182 --> 14:16.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
been named special counsel in
the case involving
the possible connections between
the Trump

14:16.355 --> 14:19.825 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
campaign and Russia in last
year's campaign.

14:19.859 --> 14:21.627 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What's your reaction to that?

14:21.660 --> 14:25.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM JEFFRESS, Baker Botts:
Excellent choice,
highly qualified, very
well-respected.

14:25.731 --> 14:26.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Couldn't have a better person.

14:26.899 --> 14:28.834 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Michael Waldman, how
about you?

14:28.868 --> 14:30.536 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What do you think of this?

14:30.569 --> 14:32.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL WALDMAN, President,
Brennan Center
for Justice: It's encouraging
news.

14:32.504 --> 14:34.406 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He is very well-respected.

14:34.440 --> 14:39.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some of the questions include,
what would
be the scope of his brief and
what is his

14:39.478 --> 14:41.213 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
level of independence?

14:41.247 --> 14:45.317 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Presumably, President Trump
isn't going to
ask him, as alleged, for his
loyalty, but

14:45.351 --> 14:50.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is he only going to look at the
potential
collusion during the campaign or
at some of

14:50.923 --> 14:56.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
these broader issues that amount
to, if true,
abuse of power and obstruction
of justice?

14:56.362 --> 15:01.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And, Mr. Jeffress, is
his representation
such that you think this should
put to rest

15:01.300 --> 15:03.235 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
any questions about this
investigation?

15:03.269 --> 15:07.039 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM JEFFRESS: I followed his
career very
closely, know him personally.

15:07.072 --> 15:10.042 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It certainly puts to rest any
question in
my mind.

15:10.075 --> 15:14.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Let's turn now to
this question
of obstruction of justice, and
whether or

15:14.747 --> 15:17.917 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not what the president has been
doing constitutes
it.

15:17.950 --> 15:23.589 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
First of all, the legal
definition under the
law, obstruction of justice, Mr.
Jeffress,

15:23.622 --> 15:25.257 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
what is it?

15:25.291 --> 15:29.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM JEFFRESS: It's corruptly
endeavoring
to influence an official
proceeding.

15:29.595 --> 15:30.562 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: Corruptly.

15:30.596 --> 15:31.563 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Corruptly, what does that mean?

15:31.597 --> 15:32.564 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM JEFFRESS: That's the key
word.

15:32.598 --> 15:34.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It means for an improper
purpose.

15:34.166 --> 15:35.868 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's defined in the law.

15:35.901 --> 15:43.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, you know, one could make a
request of
an FBI agent or, for that
matter, the head

15:43.175 --> 15:44.777 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of the FBI.

15:44.810 --> 15:47.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If not done for an improper
purpose, that
wouldn't be obstruction of
justice.

15:48.013 --> 15:49.915 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If done for an improper purpose,
it would
be.

15:49.949 --> 15:54.019 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Michael, anything you
want to add
to that or take away from that?

15:54.053 --> 15:56.755 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL WALDMAN: Well, I think
that's correct.

15:56.789 --> 16:02.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The fact that, legally, the
president can,
for example, fire the FBI
director is true,

16:02.594 --> 16:05.397 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but not if it was done for
corrupt purposes.

16:05.431 --> 16:10.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, you know, I have a right to
drive a car,
but not to drive a getaway car.

16:10.269 --> 16:16.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so that is the kind of
fact-based question
that prosecutors and juries have
to look at

16:16.375 --> 16:20.312 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and also that the court of
public opinion
needs to look at.

16:20.346 --> 16:27.086 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mr. Mueller has a legal brief,
but, ultimately,
as your story showed earlier,
Congress has

16:27.119 --> 16:31.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a very significant role to play
in looking
at the broader set of questions,
including

16:31.423 --> 16:33.258 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
this.

16:33.292 --> 16:36.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Then do you think
what the president
has done or alleged to have done
with -- with

16:37.029 --> 16:42.134 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
James Comey and his discussions
with Mr. Comey,
does that constitute obstruction
of justice

16:42.167 --> 16:43.836 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in your mind, Michael?

16:43.869 --> 16:49.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL WALDMAN: Again, assuming
that the
allegations are true, it raises
very serious

16:49.475 --> 16:55.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
questions and comes close to the
kind of obstruction
of justice that has led to
impeachment proceedings,

16:55.681 --> 16:57.616 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for example, against Richard
Nixon.

16:57.649 --> 17:00.486 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We know that he asked Mr. Comey
for his loyalty.

17:00.519 --> 17:04.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We know that, according to these
news reports,
he pulled him aside, told the
attorney general

17:04.823 --> 17:10.262 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to leave the room, and asked him
-- as his
supervisor, asked him to drop
the investigation

17:10.295 --> 17:15.134 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of his national security
adviser, and when
he didn't drop that
investigation, actually

17:15.167 --> 17:21.273 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
asked to expand it, we know that
he fired
Mr. Comey, and then went on
national television

17:21.306 --> 17:25.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to say that the reason in his
mind was -- quote
-- the Trump-Russia thing."

17:25.677 --> 17:31.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Those are all bits of evidence
that suggest
a very worrisome pattern that
could in fact

17:31.116 --> 17:33.085 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
amount to obstruction of
justice.

17:33.118 --> 17:37.289 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's certainly an abuse of power
and a risk,
I would say, to the rule of law.

17:37.322 --> 17:39.291 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Mr. Jeffress what, do
you think?

17:39.324 --> 17:46.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM JEFFRESS: Well, focusing
on the conversation
with Director Comey about
General Flynn, based

17:46.131 --> 17:52.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
